Thomas Edison Biography

Thomas Alva Edison (1847â€“1931) was an American inventor and businessman who developed many devices that greatly influenced life around the world, including the phonograph, the motion picture camera, and the long-lasting electric light bulb.

Born on February 11, 1847, in Milan, Ohio, Edison was largely self-educated. He began his career as a telegraph operator before moving into invention and entrepreneurship. Edison's first major success was the invention of the phonograph in 1877.

In 1879, he developed a practical and long-lasting electric light bulb, and in 1882, he opened the first commercial power station in New York City. He held over 1,000 patents during his lifetime and established General Electric, one of the largest and most diversified industrial corporations.

Edison's legacy is that of a prolific and practical inventor whose innovations shaped the modern industrialized world. He passed away on October 18, 1931, in West Orange, New Jersey.
